				<B>Document List: <A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=8" style="text-decoration: none;">.:: Guild Charter ::.</A>&nbsp;
<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=28" style="text-decoration: none;">.:: Loot Guidelines ::.</A>&nbsp;
<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=29" style="text-decoration: none;">.:: Raid Procedures ::.</A>&nbsp;
<br>
</B>
				<table border="0" bgcolor="gray" 
				width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr>
				<td style="color: ivory; padding: 4px" colspan="2">
				<span STYLE="font-size: 11pt; font-weight: bold;">&nbsp;&nbsp;Code of Conduct</span>
				</td></tr>
				<tr>
					<td align="left" bgcolor="white" style="font-size: 8pt">
					<A HREF="/modules.php?op=modload&amp;name=Documents&amp;file=index&id=31" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[contents]</A>
					</td>
					<td align="right" bgcolor="white" style="font-size: 8pt">
					<a href="javascript:history.go(-1)" style="text-decoration: none; font-size: x-small;">[back]</a>
					&nbsp;
					&nbsp;
					&nbsp;
					&nbsp;
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table><BR><b><u>Code of Honor</u></b><br>
<br>
All members of the guild are expected to take up the mantle of knighthood and do their best to embody the principles of honor outlined below. These are roleplaying guidelines that define the conduct of a true knight.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Courage</u></b><br>
Being a knight often means choosing the more difficult path, the personally expensive one. Be prepared to make personal sacrifices in service of the precepts and people you value. At the same time, a knight should seek wisdom to see that stupidity and courage are cousins. Courage also means taking the side of truth in all matters, rather than seeking the expedient lie. Seek the truth whenever possible, but remember to temper justice with mercy, or the pure truth can bring grief.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Prowess</u></b><br>
To seek excellence in all endeavors expected of a knight, martial and otherwise, seeking strength to be used in the service of justice, rather than in personal aggrandizement. A knight always holds himself to the highest standard.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Justice</u></b><br>
Seek always the path of 'right', unencumbered by bias or personal interest. Recognize that the sword of justice can be a terrible thing, so it must be tempered by humanity and mercy. If the 'right' you see rings true with others, and you seek it out without bending to the temptation for expediency, then you will earn renown beyond measure. <br>
<br>
<b><u>Leadership</u></b><br>
One must strive to give guidance to those in need of such guidance. By guiding and training others you strengthen not only yourself, but the guild as a whole. Pick your vassals wisely, treat them well, and always lead by example. Seek to teach those who know less than you and help them find their own paths.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Humility</u></b><br>
Value first the contributions of others; do not boast of your own accomplishments, let others do this for you. Tell the tales of others before your own, according them the renown rightfully earned through virtuous deeds. In this way the office of knighthood is well done and glorified, helping not only the gentle spoken of but also all who call themselves knights.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Courtesy</u></b><br>
One must strive to be polite and respectful in all words and deeds. Never let a harsh word or discourteous remark pass your lips, for your actions both on and off the field of battle are a reflection of not only you, but also of the Knights of Luclin as a whole. Always honor the guild, by honoring those that you interact with.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Nobility</u></b><br>
Seek great stature of character by holding to the virtues and duties of a Knight, realizing that though the ideals cannot be reached, the quality of striving towards them ennobles the spirit, growing the character from dust towards the heavens. Nobility also has the tendency to influence others, offering a compelling example of what can be done in the service of rightness. <br>
<br>
<b><u>Benevolence</u></b><br>
Be generous in so far as your resources allow; largesse used in this way counters gluttony. Remember that not all people are as fortunate as you are. Strive to help those in need with gifts and aid, both within the guild and outside of the guild. Never let greed color your decisions. <br>
<br>
<b><u>Defense</u></b><br>
Knights are sworn by oath to defend not only their own, but also the weak and inexperienced. Always strive to defend those who are not capable of defending themselves, and to protect your fellow knights.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Faith</u></b><br>
A knight must have faith in his beliefs, for faith empowers him and gives hope against the despair that human failings create. <br>
<br>
<b><u>Loyalty</u></b><br>
Be known for unwavering commitment to the people and ideals you choose to live by. There are many places where compromise is expected; loyalty is not amongst them.<br>
<br>
<b><u>Franchise</u></b><br>
Seek to emulate everything we have spoken of as sincerely as possible, not for the reason of personal gain but because it is right. Do not restrict your exploration to a small world, but seek to infuse every aspect of life with these qualities. Should you succeed in even a tiny measure then you will be well remembered for your quality and virtue. <br>
<BR><BR><span style="font-size: larger;"><b>Table of Contents</b><br>
